  <h2>Psychiatrists</h2>
  <p><strong>What they do:</strong> Psychiatrists are medical doctors who specialize in mental health. Because they have a full medical degree, they can prescribe and manage psychiatric medications — antidepressants, antipsychotics, mood stabilizers, anti-anxiety medications, ADHD medications, and more.</p>
  <p><strong>Education:</strong> Medical school (4 years) → psychiatric residency (4 years) → sometimes fellowship specialization</p>
  <p><strong>Who should see a psychiatrist:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Anyone who needs medication evaluation or management</li>
    <li>Severe depression, bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, or other serious psychiatric conditions</li>
    <li>Conditions where medication is a primary treatment component</li>
    <li>When other mental health professionals refer you for a medication evaluation</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>What psychiatrists typically don't do:</strong> Most psychiatrists today primarily manage medications rather than provide regular talk therapy. "Med check" appointments are often 15–30 minutes. For ongoing therapy, you'd typically see a therapist alongside your psychiatrist.</p>
  <p><strong>Cost:</strong> Generally the most expensive — $200–$500+ per session in the US.</p>
  <h2>Psychologists</h2>
  <p><strong>What they do:</strong> Psychologists hold doctoral degrees in psychology and are trained in both psychological assessment and psychotherapy. They can conduct comprehensive psychological testing (IQ, personality, neuropsychological assessments) as well as provide therapy.</p>
  <p><strong>Education:</strong> Doctoral degree — either a PhD (research-focused) or PsyD (clinically-focused) — typically 4–7 years post-undergraduate, plus supervised internship</p>
  <p><strong>Can they prescribe medication?</strong> In most of the world, no. Only in a few US states (New Mexico, Louisiana, Idaho, Illinois, Iowa, Colorado) can specially trained psychologists prescribe certain psychiatric medications.</p>
  <p><strong>Who should see a psychologist:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Anyone seeking comprehensive psychological assessment (learning disabilities, ADHD diagnosis, personality assessment)</li>
    <li>Complex clinical presentations</li>
    <li>When you want doctoral-level clinical training in the therapist</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Cost:</strong> Typically $150–$300+ per session in the US; often partially covered by insurance.</p>
  <h2>Therapists and Counselors</h2>
  <p>"Therapist" is a broad term covering several licensed professionals who provide talk therapy. The most common types:</p>
  <h3>Licensed Professional Counselor (LPC) / Licensed Mental Health Counselor (LMHC)</h3>
  <p>Master's degree in counseling or mental health counseling. Trained specifically to provide therapy for mental health concerns.</p>
  <h3>Licensed Clinical Social Worker (LCSW)</h3>
  <p>Master's degree in social work. Trained in both clinical mental health treatment and navigating social systems, resources, and services. LCSWs often work in community mental health, hospitals, and social service settings, as well as private practice.</p>
  <h3>Licensed Marriage and Family Therapist (LMFT)</h3>
  <p>Specializes in relationship and family systems therapy. Particularly relevant for couples therapy, family therapy, and relationship-focused concerns.</p>
  <p><strong>Who should see a therapist:</strong></p>
  <p>Most people seeking help with anxiety, depression, stress, grief, relationship difficulties, trauma, or personal growth. This is the most common starting point.</p>
  <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $80–$200 per session in the US, with significant variation by location and whether insurance is used. Online therapy with international therapists can start from $79 or lower.</p>
  <h2>Coaches vs. Therapists</h2>
  <p>Life coaches, wellness coaches, and executive coaches are not licensed mental health professionals. They don't have clinical training, can't diagnose conditions, and aren't regulated by mental health licensing boards.</p>
  <p>Coaching can be valuable for goal-setting, accountability, and performance improvement. But if you're dealing with depression, anxiety, trauma, or other clinical concerns — you need a licensed therapist or psychologist, not a coach.</p>
  <p>The distinction matters: an unlicensed coach treating clinical depression is practicing outside their scope.</p>
  <h2>Psychoanalysts</h2>
  <p>Psychoanalysts practice psychoanalysis — a long-term, insight-oriented therapy derived from Freudian and post-Freudian theory. It focuses on unconscious processes, early developmental experiences, and the therapeutic relationship.</p>
  <p>Psychoanalysts typically have a medical or master's degree plus extensive post-graduate training at a psychoanalytic institute. Sessions may occur 2–5 times per week for years.</p>
  <p>This is a small corner of the modern therapy landscape. Most people seeking therapy don't need psychoanalysis.</p>
  <h2>Who Should I See?</h2>
  <p><strong>Start with a therapist/counselor if:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>You're dealing with anxiety, depression, stress, grief, relationship issues, or personal development</li>
    <li>You want talk therapy and skill-building</li>
    <li>You want the most accessible and affordable option</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>See a psychologist if:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>You need psychological testing or formal assessment</li>
    <li>You have a complex presentation and want doctoral-level expertise</li>
    <li>Your therapist or doctor refers you</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>See a psychiatrist if:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>You think medication might be needed or has been recommended</li>
    <li>You have a severe condition (bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, severe depression, OCD requiring medication)</li>
    <li>You're already in therapy but your therapist thinks medication could help</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Many people see both a therapist and a psychiatrist.</strong> The therapist provides regular sessions for talk therapy and skill-building; the psychiatrist manages medication. These two types of professionals often communicate and collaborate.</p>
  <h2>Does It Matter Whether My Therapist Is a Psychologist or Counselor?</h2>
  <p>For most common concerns, no. Research consistently shows that <strong>outcomes are similar across therapist types</strong> when the therapist is licensed, experienced in the relevant concern, and a good fit for the client.</p>
  <p>A master's-level LCSW with 15 years of experience in anxiety treatment will typically produce better outcomes than a newly graduated PhD who hasn't yet specialized. Credentials tell you about training; experience and fit tell you about the quality of what you'll receive.</p>
  <h2>How to Find the Right Professional Online</h2>
  <p>For online therapy, the key factors are:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Licensed in their field (equivalent credentials vary by country — in South Africa, look for HPCSA registration)</li>
    <li>Specific experience with your concern</li>
    <li>Positive therapeutic fit</li>
  </ul>
