  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <p><strong>Can my therapist prescribe medication?</strong></p>
  <p>In almost all jurisdictions, therapists (LPCs, LCSWs, LMFTs, psychologists) cannot prescribe medication. For medication, you need a psychiatrist or your primary care physician.</p>
  <p><strong>Do I need a referral to see a therapist?</strong></p>
  <p>In most private pay and online therapy contexts, no. You can book directly. For insurance coverage, some plans require a referral; check with your specific insurer.</p>
  <p><strong>What's a psychiatric nurse practitioner?</strong></p>
  <p>An advanced practice nurse who can prescribe psychiatric medications in most US states. Often more accessible and affordable than psychiatrists for medication management.</p>
  <p><strong>Can a psychiatrist also do therapy?</strong></p>
  <p>Yes, some psychiatrists do provide therapy in addition to medication management — but this is increasingly rare due to economic pressures and time constraints. Most psychiatric appointments are medication-focused.</p>
